 <purpose>
	<p>
The Attachment_slot module satisfies the requirement to track selected parts as an assembly and to note when some of those parts are not installed.  A slot represents the position in which a part is or can be attached to an assembly, when it is necessary to record the history of usage of that slot.
	</p>
<note>
For the purposes of this standard, a part is either an indivisible component or an assembly of such components.
</note>
	<example number="1">	
A ship has four engines each attached at a mounting point in an engine room.  These mounting points each has an associated slot, which are identified as slot 1, slot 2, slot 3, and slot 4.  In normal usage only two main engines are are operating, the remaining two provide an operating enhancement if all four operate or a backup for the two main engines.  The attached engines are tracked against their respective slots.  If the ship does not have all of its engines installed, one or more slots are empty.  An empty slot is subject to a different maintenance regime than an installed engine.
	</example>
	<example number="2">
The pylon mounting on an aircraft wing is used to carry a radar, or fuel tank.  The mounting has an associated slot.  The fatigue life of the mounting will be determined differently depending on what is fitted at the slot and the duration of operating in that configuration which could be based on flying hours, landings, the calendar or some other measure.
	</example>
	<p>
A slot may be identified whenever there two parts that are interfaced.  If the details of this interface are required then the slot may be associated with applicable instances of the <express_ref linkend="interface:arm:Interface_arm.Interface_connector"/> and <express_ref linkend="interface:arm:Interface_arm.Interface_specification"/> entity data types.
	</p>
	<p>
A slot has an identification and may have one or more versions, and each may have one or more applicable view definitions.  A slot version may exist in the form of designs, planned individuals and realized individuals.
	</p>
	<p>
The relationships <express_ref linkend="attachment_slot:arm:Attachment_slot_arm.Product_in_slot"/>
and <express_ref linkend="attachment_slot:arm:Attachment_slot_arm.Slot_on_product"/>
identify which part or parts attach at a slot and on which part the slot is a location at which to attach one or more other parts.
	</p>
	
 </purpose>

 <inscope>
	<li>
products that have at least one physical interface, and there is a requirement to identify and distinguish between occasions on which specific parts are attached at that interface.
	</li>
	
 </inscope>

 <outscope>
	<li>
products that have no physical interface;
	</li>
	<li>
products that have a physical interface, but there is no requirement to identify and distinguish between occasions on which specific parts are attached at that interface.
	</li>
 </outscope>

